<font color="#FF0000">TRIBUTE &amp; FORTUNES OF WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8 21:09:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mustang Two Four, To be honored by a brother in arms, was in itself a great reward. I recall the following event , its embedded deep in my mind, it followed our first heavy engagement and was written about in our after action reports. From my journal (unedited)<br><br>
CAC 2-1'S DESTRUCTION<br>
Liberty Bridge, South Viet Nam <br>
16:00 Hours, November 8th, 1967<br>
From Dreams of Glory ©, 1997, Cook Barela <br><br>
(Phantom jets had just dropped napalm on the enemy a short distance from where we had set up our blocking force)<br><br>
Chunks of shrapnel, rocks, burned tree branches and foliage littered the area. A grayish white powdery residue lingered on the ground.  We stood fast as 2nd platoon Marines walked through the area ahead of us. Around us were scattered in embryonic clumps the charred bodies of a dozen enemy soldiers.  The small clump of black and gray matter did not look human. It was hard to imagine that just moments before they had been living human beings. The smell of burning flesh rose above the smell of napalm and we all knew what they were, but no one said a word. <br>
All the fighting power of the enemy and his will to resist had been snuffed out by the explosive and impressive air power we had witnesses.  Soon the radio buzzed with numerous reports of NVA soldiers turning themselves in as prisoners of war. We began to pick up serviceable weapons and other abandoned military gear. We then swept toward the remains of the villages that surrounded Dai Loc. We were moving Northwest toward the road and hill 65. <br>
It was now, just a mop up operation. As we started out across an open rice paddy field we saw a lone body of an NVA soldier. A Marine from a squad in 2nd platoon walked by the charred body that was barely breathing, he swung his M16 off his shoulder and pumped three or four rounds into the smoldering body. The body twisted and jumped as the bullets slammed into it. When I passed by, I saw the lingering effects of napalm. While the soldier may have escaped death at the tree line, the Napalm that had splattered on him had melted his face away. He looked as if he had been wearing a very distorted rubbery mask. <br>
By late afternoon our platoon had recovered 67 assorted brands of enemy rifles grenade launchers a number of satchel charges and had taken into custody 36 NVA regulars. <br>
Altogether over 250 NVA soldiers had surrendered. <br><br>
Over six hundred homes had been burned to the ground by the NVA/VC, they had killed over 200 civilians and another 60 were wounded and a hundred more were reported to be missing. India Company suffered only four WIA's none of them serious and no KIA's. 1st platoon took no causalities. <br><br>
Late that afternoon as we turned onto the road to return to Liberty Bridge we could see that the bridge was burning. We figured that it must have received some incoming mortar rounds but found out later that a Seebee using a welding tool had accidentally set the bridge on fire. When we returned to our compound, Battalion HQ's had beer brought in. <br>
Two jeeps’ each pulling small wagons filled to the top with ice covered beer, were ours to enjoy. Other cases of beer were stacked inside the jeeps. We were told that we needn’t worry about standing watch that night. The tank platoon that had accompanied us on the sweep would be manning our perimeter for the night, such were the bennies of war. <br>
While our company was credited with the annihilation of the 402d LapDuc NVA/VC Battalion, I felt bad that I hadn't fired a round.<br>
We spent late that afternoon celebrating and while the company commander and our lieutenant may have thought that we were celebrating our victory over the enemy. We were more in merriment over having been given the rest of the day off and not having to stand watch that night. <br>
By late that night sounds of the &quot;The Beatles,&quot; and the &quot;Rolling Stones,&quot; played in the background while we all sat around drinking cold beer. A reward for the devastation we had inflicted upon the enemy.  <br>
The more we drank the braver and more foolish we became. War stories started and soon we were all shit faced, falling over down drunk. We drank and cursed. We slurred our words as we talked about doggies, swabbies, and the dumb Seabees that burned the bridge, 2nd lieutenants that were stupid, and captains who were more interested in medals then in their men. <br>
By nightfall we began to talk about cowards in the Corps and of Lieutenant Colonel Chesty Puller, the Marine Corps' most decorated hero who once said, &quot;You ain't a Marine until you've done time in the brig.&quot; <br>
We talked about being busted and who had been busted the most, as well as who had done the most time in the brig. Dumont won this distinction and we cheered and slapped him on the back and drank to the little Frenchmen that didn't like being called Frenchy. We drank to little Sgt. Isaac, the skinny four-eyed Jew. We drank to his Bar Mitzvah and to the wife he didn't have. We talked about love and war. Girl friends and wives who were unfaithful. Women who never loved us back. We compared gooks we had killed and the ones that had gotten away. We traded back and forth the enemy weapons we had captured, knives, helmets, and pistols, carbines and brand new AK-47's that were traded for the right to write to a Marines sister. An hour later Jones and Keeton got into a fight over the music box and Marty cried over having shot a hole in Jones best 45 rpm records.<br><br>
As M24 has said, &quot;We must not lose sight of the fact that nobel brothers often give us recognition and respect.. the kind that really counts!&quot;<br>

